00:29:59,866 --> 00:30:01,134
Kids were stealing street signs.

772
00:30:01,167 --> 00:30:02,603
‐ Anybody else hurt?
‐ No, girl's fine.

773
00:30:02,636 --> 00:30:04,070
She's in the car
with my partner.

774
00:30:04,104 --> 00:30:05,506
Okay, we're gonna
sit you up now.

775
00:30:05,539 --> 00:30:07,040
What's your name?

776
00:30:07,073 --> 00:30:08,141
Andrew.

777
00:30:09,643 --> 00:30:10,977
Don't I know you?

778
00:30:13,479 --> 00:30:15,015
That your daughter?

779
00:30:15,048 --> 00:30:16,316
'She's not under arrest?'

780
00:30:16,349 --> 00:30:17,518
'No, situations like this'

781
00:30:17,551 --> 00:30:19,152
we just like to scare them
a little bit.

782
00:30:19,185 --> 00:30:21,021
Take them down to the station,
call their parents.

783
00:30:21,054 --> 00:30:22,623
‐ 'They'll release her to me?'
‐ 'I'll call the sergeant.'

784
00:30:22,656 --> 00:30:24,525
‐ Don't think it'd be a problem.
‐ I'd appreciate that.

785
00:30:24,558 --> 00:30:26,059
Got a phone I can use?

786
00:30:26,092 --> 00:30:27,928
I adjusted her meds,
have the nurse call

787
00:30:27,961 --> 00:30:29,429
if she has any questions.

788
00:30:29,462 --> 00:30:30,931
‐ 'Sandy.'
‐ Hey.

789
00:30:30,964 --> 00:30:32,198
Still got time
for a wound check?

790
00:30:32,232 --> 00:30:34,034
Uh, I thought you had
to leave AMA.

791
00:30:34,067 --> 00:30:35,201
Oh, it wasn't bothering me

792
00:30:35,235 --> 00:30:37,037
until I jammed it
rolling some hose.

793
00:30:37,070 --> 00:30:38,872
‐ Still bleeding?
‐ I don't think so.

794
00:30:38,905 --> 00:30:40,406
‐ Come on, let's take a look.
‐ Okay.

795
00:30:40,440 --> 00:30:42,643
'What happens when
you're on call?'

796
00:30:42,676 --> 00:30:44,545
We work 12‐hour shifts.

797
00:30:44,578 --> 00:30:45,979
7:00 a. m. to 7:00 p. m?

798
00:30:46,012 --> 00:30:47,313
Half the time.

799
00:30:47,347 --> 00:30:48,982
And the other half,
you work overnight?

800
00:30:49,015 --> 00:30:51,317
There's always a surgeon
in‐house.

801
00:30:51,351 --> 00:30:54,320
‐ So, you cover weekends too?
‐ Sometimes.

802
00:30:54,354 --> 00:30:55,522
Well, looking at your schedule,
it appears

803
00:30:55,556 --> 00:30:56,557
that over half your shifts

804
00:30:56,590 --> 00:30:58,091
are weekends or overnights.

805
00:30:58,124 --> 00:30:59,593
Well, I'd have to check.

806
00:30:59,626 --> 00:31:01,461
Take me through what happens
when a gunshot victim

807
00:31:01,494 --> 00:31:03,630
enters the ER.

808
00:31:03,664 --> 00:31:05,231
Well, I evaluate the patient

809
00:31:05,265 --> 00:31:07,901
and I take them
to the OR, if necessary.

810
00:31:07,934 --> 00:31:09,135
Gunshot to the chest.

811
00:31:09,169 --> 00:31:11,037
How long of an operation
is that?

812
00:31:11,071 --> 00:31:12,673
‐ Well, that depends.
‐ 'On what?'

813
00:31:12,706 --> 00:31:15,275
The path of the bullet,
extent of vascular damage

814
00:31:15,308 --> 00:31:18,612
if bypass is necessary
for cardiac repair.

815
00:31:18,645 --> 00:31:21,014
So, it could take
over an hour?

816
00:31:21,047 --> 00:31:22,683
I'd say three hours
was a reasonable estimate.

817
00:31:22,716 --> 00:31:24,651
Sometimes longer?
Five hours?

818
00:31:25,519 --> 00:31:27,353
Sometimes.

819
00:31:27,387 --> 00:31:29,122
'So, if a patient comes in
at 6:30 p. m.'

820
00:31:29,155 --> 00:31:31,992
who takes over for you at 7:00
when you go home to Reese?

821
00:31:32,025 --> 00:31:34,060
Well, I try to get someone
to cover for me.

822
00:31:34,094 --> 00:31:36,162
And if you can't?

823
00:31:36,196 --> 00:31:37,964
Then I stay with the patient.

824
00:31:37,998 --> 00:31:39,966
If an operation takes five hours

825
00:31:40,000 --> 00:31:41,067
you'll be there till midnight?

826
00:31:42,435 --> 00:31:43,904
That's a rare situation.

827
00:31:44,705 --> 00:31:46,540
But it happens?

828
00:31:46,573 --> 00:31:48,942
It's possible.

829
00:31:48,975 --> 00:31:50,410
So, when you're tied up
in surgery all night

830
00:31:50,443 --> 00:31:52,245
'who's looking after Reese?'

831
00:31:52,278 --> 00:31:55,315
Well, I have the support
of family and friends.

832
00:31:55,348 --> 00:31:57,117
Like Dr. Finch, for example?

833
00:31:57,150 --> 00:31:58,251
Yes.

834
00:31:58,284 --> 00:32:00,286
Cleo is very good with Reese.

835
00:32:00,320 --> 00:32:02,022
'Yes, we've already
covered that.'

836
00:32:02,055 --> 00:32:03,690
Who else helps you out?

837
00:32:03,724 --> 00:32:06,059
My sister, Jackie picks him up
from school if I have to work.

838
00:32:06,092 --> 00:32:07,994
‐ And makes him dinner?
‐ Sometimes.

839
00:32:08,028 --> 00:32:10,163
And puts him to bed while
you're working the night shift?

840
00:32:10,196 --> 00:32:11,297
That's right.

841
00:32:11,331 --> 00:32:12,398
Is she always available?

842
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:15,235
Jackie's become like a mother

843
00:32:15,268 --> 00:32:16,603
to Reese these last few months.

844
00:32:16,637 --> 00:32:18,171
But initially, after Carla died

845
00:32:18,204 --> 00:32:19,606
Jackie wasn't so receptive
to the idea

846
00:32:19,640 --> 00:32:21,508
of caring for Reese, was she?

847
00:32:21,542 --> 00:32:22,743
It was a tough time.

848
00:32:22,776 --> 00:32:24,645
She has her own children,
doesn't she?

849
00:32:24,678 --> 00:32:26,412
Joanie, her daughter.

850
00:32:26,446 --> 00:32:27,548
Wasn't there a boy?

851
00:32:29,516 --> 00:32:31,351
Yeah, uh, Jesse, my nephew.

852
00:32:31,384 --> 00:32:33,520
He died last year.

853
00:32:33,554 --> 00:32:35,421
The death was gang‐related,
right?

854
00:32:35,455 --> 00:32:37,490
‐ Objection.
‐ He can answer the question.

855
00:32:40,561 --> 00:32:42,228
Yes.

856
00:32:42,262 --> 00:32:44,565
How is your sister handling
that loss?

857
00:32:44,598 --> 00:32:47,233
You know, I'm sorry.
I don't, uh..

858
00:32:47,267 --> 00:32:50,003
I don't see how this pertains
to my fitness as a father.

859
00:32:50,036 --> 00:32:51,437
Your Honor,
this is far afield.

860
00:32:51,471 --> 00:32:53,273
Goes to the stability
of the person he's identified

861
00:32:53,306 --> 00:32:54,508
as primary caregiver.

862
00:32:54,541 --> 00:32:56,643
I'll give some latitude.

863
00:32:56,677 --> 00:32:59,145
Is Jackie under the care
of a psychiatrist?

864
00:32:59,179 --> 00:33:00,280
I don't know.

865
00:33:00,313 --> 00:33:01,414
For situational depression

866
00:33:01,447 --> 00:33:02,583
and pathologic grieving?

867
00:33:02,616 --> 00:33:04,217
She lost her son.

868
00:33:04,250 --> 00:33:06,319
Is she currently
being managed by medication‐‐

869
00:33:06,352 --> 00:33:07,453
This has nothing
to do with Reese

870
00:33:07,487 --> 00:33:08,488
or my ability
to care for him.

871
00:33:08,522 --> 00:33:10,090
...whose side effects include

872
00:33:10,123 --> 00:33:12,125
insomnia, sedation
and anxiety?

873
00:33:12,158 --> 00:33:13,560
Gentlemen!

874
00:33:13,594 --> 00:33:15,361
Why don't you ask me
what kind of father I am?

875
00:33:15,395 --> 00:33:17,063
Why don't you ask me
about how I was there

876
00:33:17,097 --> 00:33:18,632
when he was born prematurely

877
00:33:18,665 --> 00:33:20,801
how I stayed in the hospital
in the NICU

878
00:33:20,834 --> 00:33:22,569
watching over him,
making tough decisions

879
00:33:22,603 --> 00:33:24,037
and praying over him
day and night?

880
00:33:24,070 --> 00:33:25,238
Why don't you ask me that?

881
00:33:25,271 --> 00:33:26,540
Your Honor,
a moment with my client.

882
00:33:26,573 --> 00:33:28,174
Dr. Benton‐‐

883
00:33:28,208 --> 00:33:29,375
Your Honor, there's no question
before the court.

884
00:33:29,409 --> 00:33:31,444
No, why don't you ask me
about Reese

885
00:33:31,477 --> 00:33:33,747
so I can tell you that
there's nothing more important

886
00:33:33,780 --> 00:33:35,348
to me in this world
than my son?

887
00:33:35,381 --> 00:33:36,783
Why don't you ask me that?

888
00:33:51,231 --> 00:33:52,198
You can't let that happen again.

889
00:33:52,232 --> 00:33:53,299
They were provoking him.

890
00:33:53,333 --> 00:33:54,434
You better get used
to it, Peter.

891
00:33:54,467 --> 00:33:55,468
I said what I had to say.

892
00:33:55,501 --> 00:33:56,537
Well, I hope you feel better

893
00:33:56,570 --> 00:33:57,771
'cause it sure didn't help.

894
00:33:57,804 --> 00:33:59,372
What did the judge say
in chambers?

895
00:33:59,405 --> 00:34:02,108
That he was impressed
with Roger's availability.

896
00:34:02,142 --> 00:34:03,844
‐ Availability?
‐ I'm available to Reese.

897
00:34:03,877 --> 00:34:05,546
We're gonna have
to make a better showing.

898
00:34:05,579 --> 00:34:06,580
Alright.
I'll do better tomorrow.

899
00:34:06,613 --> 00:34:08,481
That's not gonna do it.

900
00:34:08,515 --> 00:34:10,216
Your hours are hurting us.

901
00:34:10,250 --> 00:34:11,351
He's a surgeon.

902
00:34:11,384 --> 00:34:13,153
'It goes with the job.'

903
00:34:13,186 --> 00:34:14,320
Do you wanna keep your son?

904
00:34:14,354 --> 00:34:15,756
What do you think?

905
00:34:15,789 --> 00:34:17,724
That you need
to start setting priorities

906
00:34:17,758 --> 00:34:19,359
'and making some hard choices.'

907
00:34:19,392 --> 00:34:20,627
'That's what I think.'

908
00:34:26,600 --> 00:34:27,601
How well do you know Andrew?

909
00:34:29,169 --> 00:34:30,370
What's that supposed to mean?

910
00:34:31,471 --> 00:34:33,774
Does he do drugs?

911
00:34:33,807 --> 00:34:35,609
‐ I don't think so.
‐ Are you sure?

912
00:34:40,814 --> 00:34:43,383
‐ What's this?
‐ Results of his tox screen.

913
00:34:43,416 --> 00:34:45,786
He tested positive
for marijuana.

914
00:34:45,819 --> 00:34:48,454
Aren't you supposed
to keep that confidential?

915
00:34:48,488 --> 00:34:49,890
Were you smoking with him?

916
00:34:49,923 --> 00:34:51,725
No.

917
00:34:51,758 --> 00:34:53,326
Have you ever smoked with him?

918
00:34:53,359 --> 00:34:55,529
I wouldn't do that.

919
00:34:55,562 --> 00:34:56,730
Good.

920
00:34:56,763 --> 00:34:58,264
Then you'll test negative.

921
00:35:02,302 --> 00:35:04,404
Are you serious?

922
00:35:04,437 --> 00:35:05,572
You don't trust me?

923
00:35:05,606 --> 00:35:07,574
I trusted you to go home
after school.

924
00:35:07,608 --> 00:35:09,610
Dad, he was gonna
drop me off

925
00:35:09,643 --> 00:35:10,677
but then,
he wanted to stop.

926
00:35:10,711 --> 00:35:12,846
We agreed no rides.

927
00:35:12,879 --> 00:35:15,916
‐ I missed the bus.
‐ You should have called me.

928
00:35:15,949 --> 00:35:17,483
I didn't wanna bother you.

929
00:35:19,452 --> 00:35:20,887
Sure didn't work out that way.

930
00:35:22,756 --> 00:35:24,891
You want me to pee in a cup?

931
00:35:24,925 --> 00:35:26,192
Yep.

932
00:35:28,328 --> 00:35:30,363
Yes, a gram of Ceftazidime.

933
00:35:30,396 --> 00:35:32,498
Michael, did the family choose
a mortuary yet?

934
00:35:32,533 --> 00:35:33,700
‐ What?
‐ Rudy Escalona.

935
00:35:33,734 --> 00:35:34,768
We need to get him
to the morgue.

936
00:35:34,801 --> 00:35:37,270
No. Not the ICU, the ER.
Thanks.

937
00:35:37,303 --> 00:35:38,371
Oh, you need me to do something?

938
00:35:38,404 --> 00:35:40,240
Ask Frank
for the decedent packet.

939
00:35:42,342 --> 00:35:43,810
‐ Luka?
‐ Hmm?

940
00:35:43,844 --> 00:35:47,213
You weren't here so I gave
Collins the gent first.

941
00:35:47,247 --> 00:35:48,615
Thanks.

942
00:35:48,649 --> 00:35:51,217
I...I had to go out.

943
00:35:51,251 --> 00:35:52,719
Everything okay?

944
00:35:52,753 --> 00:35:55,221
She's leaving town.

945
00:35:55,255 --> 00:35:56,723
‐ Why?
‐ I don't know.

946
00:35:56,757 --> 00:35:58,925
Dr. Kovac,
exam four's vomiting blood.

947
00:35:58,959 --> 00:36:00,961
What about the baby?

948
00:36:00,994 --> 00:36:02,362
There is no baby.

949
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:08,468
I started another line
on Zahler.

950
00:36:08,501 --> 00:36:09,903
Did you have a written order?

951
00:36:09,936 --> 00:36:11,638
It was right up there.

952
00:36:11,672 --> 00:36:14,641
Why was Abby about to discharge
my bowel obstruction?

953
00:36:14,675 --> 00:36:15,876
I have no idea.

954
00:36:15,909 --> 00:36:17,443
Because you can't write
between the lines.

955
00:36:17,477 --> 00:36:19,746
‐ Oh, sorry.
‐ 'Carter, is this one yours?

956
00:36:19,780 --> 00:36:21,915
'Twenty five‐year‐old woman,
severe allergic reactions‐‐'

957
00:36:21,948 --> 00:36:23,884
‐ Mrs. Urman?
‐ 'Gave her 50 of Benadryl.'

958
00:36:23,917 --> 00:36:25,986
‐ What happened?
‐ I guess you were right.

959
00:36:26,019 --> 00:36:27,921
‐ We followed our bliss.
‐ Where?

960
00:36:27,954 --> 00:36:28,989
To our pickup truck.

961
00:36:29,022 --> 00:36:30,223
I figured we'd be safe right

962
00:36:30,256 --> 00:36:31,758
by the hospital, so, uh..

963
00:36:31,792 --> 00:36:33,660
I'll get her started.
300 of cimetidine.

964
00:36:33,694 --> 00:36:35,629
I will be right there.

965
00:36:35,662 --> 00:36:37,731
Ooh, that's a very nice suit.

966
00:36:37,764 --> 00:36:39,332
Thanks. I was in court all day.

967
00:36:39,365 --> 00:36:40,634
‐ A patient?
‐ No.

968
00:36:40,667 --> 00:36:42,936
‐ Something wrong?
‐ No. Everything's cool.

969
00:36:42,969 --> 00:36:44,671
Dr. Benton, they need you
in the OR.

970
00:36:48,942 --> 00:36:50,677
Mr. Escalona.

971
00:36:50,711 --> 00:36:53,547
Uh, if you'd like,
the nurse said

972
00:36:53,580 --> 00:36:55,481
that we can make arrangements
for the funeral home.

973
00:36:57,551 --> 00:37:01,021
W‐we used, uh, Rose Hills
when his mother died.

974
00:37:01,054 --> 00:37:03,256
But I‐I never
thought that..

975
00:37:09,663 --> 00:37:11,832
He was a good kid.

976
00:37:11,865 --> 00:37:13,333
He made everybody smile.

977
00:37:14,835 --> 00:37:16,603
Jorge..

978
00:37:16,637 --> 00:37:17,904
'...he was the serious one.'

979
00:37:19,640 --> 00:37:21,007
I didn't mean
to lose my temper.

980
00:37:22,676 --> 00:37:24,310
It's been a hard day,
you know?

981
00:37:25,812 --> 00:37:26,980
He doesn't wanna see me.

982
00:37:28,549 --> 00:37:29,783
He doesn't understand.

983
00:37:32,452 --> 00:37:34,287
You, uh, should give him
a shot.

984
00:37:35,922 --> 00:37:37,323
You know,
he might surprise you.

985
00:38:18,498 --> 00:38:19,766
Sorry to be brief

986
00:38:19,800 --> 00:38:22,603
but my nanny gets off
in six minutes.

987
00:38:22,636 --> 00:38:24,671
Diane Pruitt,
GSW to the head.

988
00:38:24,705 --> 00:38:27,007
Transplant teams are flying
in from Indiana and Michigan.

989
00:38:27,040 --> 00:38:28,775
‐ The gas station robbery.
‐ Yes.

990
00:38:28,809 --> 00:38:30,911
Romano has agreed
to a non‐heart beating protocol.

991
00:38:30,944 --> 00:38:31,978
When did we start doing that?

992
00:38:32,012 --> 00:38:33,346
Today, apparently.

993
00:38:34,548 --> 00:38:35,849
That's the husband over there.

994
00:38:35,882 --> 00:38:36,917
If you could review
the procedure

995
00:38:36,950 --> 00:38:38,418
with him once more?

996
00:38:38,451 --> 00:38:39,686
He's already consented, right?

997
00:38:39,720 --> 00:38:40,721
Yeah, of course.

998
00:38:40,754 --> 00:38:42,623
So what is there to talk about?

999
00:38:42,656 --> 00:38:44,057
Uh, the man needs
some reassurance.

1000
00:38:44,090 --> 00:38:46,527
Elizabeth, you had him
for 12 hours. You deal with him.

1001
00:38:46,560 --> 00:38:48,328
He wants to talk
to the operating surgeon.

1002
00:38:50,163 --> 00:38:51,732
Peter, what's the matter?

1003
00:38:53,466 --> 00:38:54,601
Nothing. Go home.

1004
00:38:56,503 --> 00:38:58,839
Mr. Pruitt?
Hi.

1005
00:38:58,872 --> 00:39:01,374
I'm Dr. Benton. I'll be
coordinating the procedure.

1006
00:39:01,407 --> 00:39:02,909
As soon as the out‐of‐state team
gets here

1007
00:39:02,943 --> 00:39:04,545
we'll take her to the OR.

1008
00:39:04,578 --> 00:39:05,646
Okay.

1009
00:39:05,679 --> 00:39:08,048
I, uh, I tried to explain it

1010
00:39:08,081 --> 00:39:11,151
to her, but, uh,
she's too young.

1011
00:39:11,184 --> 00:39:13,486
I don't know how
I'm gonna do this by myself.

1012
00:39:15,188 --> 00:39:18,124
Well, you'll do the best
you can.

1013
00:39:18,158 --> 00:39:21,461
You're supposed
to be on light duty.

1014
00:39:21,494 --> 00:39:22,629
I was moving some gear.

1015
00:39:22,663 --> 00:39:24,998
No, you went on a run.

1016
00:39:25,031 --> 00:39:27,467
I get a little stir crazy.

1017
00:39:28,669 --> 00:39:30,070
Okay.

1018
00:39:30,103 --> 00:39:32,639
Looks pretty good,
no sign of infection.

1019
00:39:32,673 --> 00:39:34,074
That's it?

1020
00:39:34,107 --> 00:39:35,942
No. You need a new bandage.

1021
00:39:41,114 --> 00:39:43,617
So, is, uh..

1022
00:39:43,650 --> 00:39:46,653
...Captain Devlin
still at the seven‐five?

1023
00:39:46,687 --> 00:39:48,488
I know the name.

1024
00:39:48,522 --> 00:39:49,790
Yeah, those guys
used to hang out

1025
00:39:49,823 --> 00:39:52,726
at a place called
the, um, Moose and Squirrel.

1026
00:39:52,759 --> 00:39:55,495
Yeah. Every Friday night.

1027
00:39:55,529 --> 00:39:56,797
That was a fun place.

1028
00:39:59,099 --> 00:40:00,767
Uh, you should have someone

1029
00:40:00,801 --> 00:40:03,469
remove the stitches
in four days.

1030
00:40:03,504 --> 00:40:04,838
I know where to find you.

1031
00:40:09,810 --> 00:40:11,745
Listen, Sandy..

1032
00:40:11,778 --> 00:40:13,213
Oh, gosh, I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.

1033
00:40:13,246 --> 00:40:14,915
‐ Oh, I bunched it up.
‐ That's alright.

1034
00:40:14,948 --> 00:40:16,149
What were you saying?

1035
00:40:17,684 --> 00:40:18,885
Do you wanna do something?

1036
00:40:20,153 --> 00:40:21,755
Excuse me?

1037
00:40:21,788 --> 00:40:23,724
Uh, sometime?
You know, something.

1038
00:40:24,891 --> 00:40:26,059
Something?

1039
00:40:26,092 --> 00:40:27,493
Uh, I don't know.

1040
00:40:27,528 --> 00:40:30,531
Lunch, or a movie,
or ice fishing?

1041
00:40:34,100 --> 00:40:36,803
‐ Like, go out?
‐ Yeah.

1042
00:40:36,837 --> 00:40:39,873
I mean, unless I'm totally
off base here.

1043
00:40:39,906 --> 00:40:41,575
No.

1044
00:40:41,608 --> 00:40:42,976
No, you're on base.

1045
00:40:49,015 --> 00:40:50,751
How's it going?

1046
00:40:50,784 --> 00:40:52,886
Fine.

1047
00:40:52,919 --> 00:40:55,221
Your drug screen came back.

1048
00:40:55,255 --> 00:40:56,690
Everything was negative.

1049
00:40:58,158 --> 00:40:59,660
Don't look so disappointed.

1050
00:41:05,832 --> 00:41:06,900
I know you're upset.

1051
00:41:09,002 --> 00:41:10,737
But I had to do this

1052
00:41:10,771 --> 00:41:12,105
because I want you to be safe.

1053
00:41:13,974 --> 00:41:15,809
I care more about that

1054
00:41:15,842 --> 00:41:17,844
than about your being angry
with me.

1055
00:41:21,548 --> 00:41:22,983
I wanna be able
to trust you.

1056
00:41:25,652 --> 00:41:27,253
It's something we both
have to work at.

1057
00:41:29,656 --> 00:41:30,857
Can I go now?

1058
00:41:34,695 --> 00:41:36,830
‐ Is the recipient ready?
‐ Yeah. All I need is a liver.

1059
00:41:36,863 --> 00:41:38,765
Alright. The heart team
gets first crack.

1060
00:41:38,799 --> 00:41:40,100
But tell them
to make it snappy.

1061
00:41:42,002 --> 00:41:44,004
Sternal saw's up.

1062
00:41:44,037 --> 00:41:46,106
Open the O Dexon,
atraumatic needle.

1063
00:41:47,273 --> 00:41:49,776
‐ All set?
‐ 'Good to go.'

1064
00:41:49,810 --> 00:41:51,645
After two minutes
of cardiac arrest

1065
00:41:51,678 --> 00:41:53,113
I'll call it, and then
we'll begin procurement.

1066
00:41:53,146 --> 00:41:54,314
How's her oxygenation?

1067
00:41:54,347 --> 00:41:55,816
'Fine. Satting at 100 percent.'

1068
00:41:55,849 --> 00:41:57,751
'Good. Turn it off.'

1069
00:41:57,784 --> 00:42:00,253
Respiratory support
discontinued at 20:37.

1070
00:42:04,858 --> 00:42:07,260
Oh, they're sweet.
I hope they get pregnant.

1071
00:42:07,293 --> 00:42:08,629
Shouldn't be a problem.

1072
00:42:08,662 --> 00:42:10,130
The endocrinologist can wash
the sperm

1073
00:42:10,163 --> 00:42:12,065
and then it's safe
to artificially inseminate.

1074
00:42:12,098 --> 00:42:14,267
Hmm.
That's a new one.

1075
00:42:14,300 --> 00:42:17,638
Just goes to teach you
never to doubt my diagnoses.

1076
00:42:17,671 --> 00:42:20,140
Yeah, no matter
how loony they are.

1077
00:42:20,173 --> 00:42:21,708
I can't believe
they did it

1078
00:42:21,742 --> 00:42:23,877
in the back
of a pickup truck.

1079
00:42:23,910 --> 00:42:25,912
‐ They had a camper shell.
‐ How do you know?

1080
00:42:25,946 --> 00:42:27,147
‐ I saw it.
‐ You did?

1081
00:42:27,180 --> 00:42:28,214
Yes. In the front
of the hospital.

1082
00:42:28,248 --> 00:42:30,083
It's their honeymoon suite.

1083
00:42:30,116 --> 00:42:31,284
Very weird.

1084
00:42:31,317 --> 00:42:32,318
Not so weird.

1085
00:42:32,352 --> 00:42:33,820
Ferris wheel, that's weird.

1086
00:42:35,288 --> 00:42:37,724
‐ Really?
‐ I‐I was young.

1087
00:42:37,758 --> 00:42:39,860
It was my first real boyfriend.

1088
00:42:41,695 --> 00:42:42,863
Where else?

1089
00:42:42,896 --> 00:42:44,130
Your turn.

1090
00:42:44,164 --> 00:42:46,266
Camping. Where else?

1091
00:42:46,299 --> 00:42:48,869
In a tent? That's the best
you can do?

1092
00:42:48,902 --> 00:42:49,970
Uh..

1093
00:42:53,640 --> 00:42:55,776
On a train to Seattle.

1094
00:42:55,809 --> 00:42:58,244
Really?
With who?

1095
00:42:58,278 --> 00:43:00,180
I was by myself..

1096
00:43:00,213 --> 00:43:01,347
...but it was memorable.

1097
00:43:07,654 --> 00:43:09,389
Mm. It's cold.

1098
00:43:09,422 --> 00:43:11,391
Yeah. We should probably go in.

1099
00:43:11,424 --> 00:43:12,759
Yeah.

1100
00:43:22,102 --> 00:43:24,270
Carter..

1101
00:43:24,304 --> 00:43:26,673
You don't have any allergies
I should know about, do you?

1102
00:43:32,045 --> 00:43:33,046
Oops.

1103
00:43:34,848 --> 00:43:35,982
Where were we?

1104
00:43:37,684 --> 00:43:39,920
‐ How long has it been?
‐ Forty nine minutes.

1105
00:43:39,953 --> 00:43:41,888
Tissues could be
getting ischemic.

1106
00:43:41,922 --> 00:43:44,925
Alright, let's send an ABG,
lytes and a lactate.

1107
00:43:44,958 --> 00:43:45,959
Who's in charge here?

1108
00:43:45,992 --> 00:43:47,227
I ordered liver an hour ago

1109
00:43:47,260 --> 00:43:49,730
and I haven't seen my waitress
since.

1110
00:43:49,763 --> 00:43:51,131
The patient's breathing
on her own.

1111
00:43:51,164 --> 00:43:53,800
Ugh. How inconsiderate.

1112
00:43:53,834 --> 00:43:55,235
Well, this could take hours.

1113
00:43:55,268 --> 00:43:57,771
Page me when she goes.

1114
00:43:57,804 --> 00:43:59,339
What do you wanna do,
Dr. Benton?

1115
00:44:06,780 --> 00:44:08,048
Let's just wait.
